properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Severe thunderstorms are possible this afternoon and tonight. The first round of severe thunderstorms is expected to wind down by late afternoon. Another round of severe thunderstorms appears likely late this evening into tomorrow morning. The main threats are torrential rainfall, wind gusts up to 90 km/h, and loonie sized hail. ### Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm. For more information: http://www.emergencymanagementontario.ca/english/beprepared/beprepared.html.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of very dangerous thunderstorms that may be capable of producing damaging wind gusts, damaging hail and flooding rain. Thunderstorms that produced hail and heavy rainfall this morning across southern Manitoba continues to track eastward. Another round of severe storms are expected to develop over western Manitoba later this afternoon along a cold front. These storms will develop into a squall line and track eastward across southern Manitoba this evening and into eastern Manitoba overnight. Heavy rainfall can be expected again with fairly widespread 50 to 100 mm of rain possible. Combined with the heavy rainfall this morning, significant flooding can be expected with the already over saturated ground. Large hail and wind gusts over 100 km/h along the squall line are also likely. Isolated tornadoes with any embedded supercells over the southern Red River Valley this evening cannot be ruled out. ### Very strong wind gusts can damage buildings, down trees and blow large vehicles off the road. Heavy downpours are likely to cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Post-tropical Storm Humberto. The next information statement will be issued by 09:00 p.m. ADT. Gale to storm force winds continue over the southeastern Maritime waters and will spread across the southern Grand banks this afternoon and overnight. 1. Summary of basic information at 03:00 p.m. ADT. Location: Near 43.4 North 56.5 West. About 450 kilometres southwest of Cape Race. Maximum sustained winds: 110 kilometres per hour. Present movement: Northeast at 40 kilometres per hour. Minimum central pressure: 975 millibars. 2. Public weather impacts and warnings summary. No significant effects are expected over land. a. Wind. No significant wind expected. b. Rainfall. Heavy bands of rain may reach southern portions of the Avalon Peninsula as Post-Tropical Storm Humberto tracks across the Grand Banks tonight and early Saturday morning. c. Surge/Waves. Swells of 2 to 3 metres are now approaching the Atlantic coast of Nova Scotia, with 3 to 5 metre swells expected to reach southern Newfoundland tonight and early Saturday. Waves will break higher along some areas of the coastline, and dangerous rip currents are possible. 3. Marine weather impacts and warnings summary. Storm warnings are in effect for Laurentian Fan, Southwestern Grand Banks and Southeastern Grand Banks. Gale warnings are in effect for Sable - eastern half, East Scotian Slope - eastern half, Banquereau - southern half, Northeast Coast and East Coast of Newfoundland, Funk Island bank and the Northern Grand Banks. Gale to Storm Force winds are forecast over southeastern portions of the Maritimes marine district today and over marine areas south and east of Newfoundland beginning this evening and into Saturday. Large waves of 7 to 10 metres are forecast to continue over the southeastern offshore waters this afternoon and tonight. Some of these waves could exceed 10 metres southeast of the track as the centre continues over Laurentian Fan and over the southern Grand Banks overnight into Saturday. Forecaster(s): McArthur. ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
